Euro needs a migration restart
Brussels — Over 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching all summer for a safe port where their passengers can land.
Refugee and migrant camps on Lesbos Island in Greece are overcrowded, and the conditions in other Libyan reception camps are similar.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement that prevented migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help immigrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
During 2015–16, the number of refugees and migrants arriving in the EU surged — many fleeing the Syrian war — which greatly affected trust within the EU.
The massive inflow of immigrants eroded governments' confidence in managing the EU's external borders and asylum systems, and highlighted the failure of cooperation with countries of origin.
Therefore, immigration has become a political football, a favorite topic for populist politicians.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control over immigration while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this reason, the EU needs to revise four aspects of its policy and mobilize member states to take action for the benefit of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping internal borders open.
No country that allows free movement of its people, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, would outsource control of its external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task, as well as a national responsibility.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should deploy joint patrols with member states — including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them together has led the asylum system to the brink of collapse; handling them separately would help ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns under protected rights.
Addressing the EU's real economic and social needs requires an effective blue card or green card policy for economic migrants, along with an overall immigration target.
This cannot wait for the next immigration crisis to introduce these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Secondly, policies must clearly define which migrants are welcome.
Thirdly, member states must answer the question of what kind of EU support is needed to achieve a smooth immigration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be made visible to facilitate the return of illegal migrants to their countries of origin.
Admittedly, under the EU treaties, each member state needs to manage immigration from outside the EU on its own.
However, reaching an agreement on an overall EU immigration target would be a major step forward.
In return, member states could specify the source countries and specific criteria they want for economic migrants, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to receive immigrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on indicators such as source countries, skill levels, and age groups.
Europe can also do this.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all requirement for mandatory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU must be abolished.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Additionally, it cannot be expected that the EU's frontline member states alone can resolve the issue of illegal migrants crossing external borders.
The reception camps are overcrowded, and immigrants are subjected to abuse by the authorities or driven north.
The responsibility of the first member state that the immigrants arrive in must be supplemented by the EU's cohesion policy.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to improve the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
After improving the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions, the asylum application process can also be shared among member states.
The fourth, the EU should build stronger mutually beneficial cooperation with source countries and transit countries.
These connections are essential to repatriate immigrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU back to their home countries.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in security, trade, energy, agriculture, fishing, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration targets, as well as skill cooperation to prepare for jobs in Europe, can provide third countries that desire stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes population explosions in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; disease outbreaks; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on reshaping stability and reducing risks through support for security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in these areas can make investments safer, release private and domestic finance, thus achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from an unconscious reaction to migration crises toward a more consistent and sustained approach, regardless of internal or external matters.
We must never miss this opportunity.
